19
00:00:53,517 --> 00:00:57,519
Most of my tips come from my traditional animation experience.

20
00:00:57,519 --> 00:01:01,680
They will be the most useful for the few traditional animators in the room, but that said, I'll

21
00:01:01,680 --> 00:01:04,402
try to make the tips useful for 3D animators as well.

22
00:01:06,556 --> 00:01:10,637
First tip, nail down your main poses as soon as you can.

23
00:01:10,637 --> 00:01:12,118
I had a lot of trouble with this robot

24
00:01:12,118 --> 00:01:13,718
before I started doing this.

25
00:01:13,718 --> 00:01:15,179
I wish I had my first attempts,

26
00:01:15,179 --> 00:01:16,920
but they were not worth keeping.

27
00:01:16,920 --> 00:01:19,160
I used to spend too much time

28
00:01:19,160 --> 00:01:20,821
in the rough stages of my animations,

29
00:01:20,821 --> 00:01:23,402
without finalizing any of the main poses

30
00:01:23,402 --> 00:01:25,323
until I had already done a lot of animating.

31
00:01:25,323 --> 00:01:26,843
But then sometimes I would find that,

32
00:01:26,843 --> 00:01:29,184
because I hadn't fully fleshed out the major keys,

33
00:01:29,184 --> 00:01:31,425
I didn't notice serious problems,

34
00:01:31,425 --> 00:01:34,006
and I would often have to fix a lot of my animation,

35
00:01:34,006 --> 00:01:34,826
if not start over.

36
00:01:36,279 --> 00:01:38,660
So these days I like to nail things down early,

37
00:01:38,660 --> 00:01:40,781
because it prevents some problems down the line

38
00:01:40,781 --> 00:01:45,863
and it eliminates the uncertainty of whether my animation will work or not.

39
00:01:45,863 --> 00:01:50,185
I find the most stressful period of animating, especially on a deadline,

40
00:01:50,185 --> 00:01:54,246
is the time up until I know for sure that the animation is going to work.

41
00:01:54,246 --> 00:01:56,527
I know that once the poses are nailed down and they work,

42
00:01:56,527 --> 00:01:59,868
at the very least I won't have to start over and I can relax a little bit.

43
00:02:01,366 --> 00:02:03,987
Now for 3D animators, I'd summarize this tip as,

44
00:02:03,987 --> 00:02:06,768
focus on the poses before you focus on the motion.

45
00:02:06,768 --> 00:02:07,988
If you can work that way.

46
00:02:07,988 --> 00:02:10,509
I know some 3D animators will do things like,

47
00:02:10,509 --> 00:02:13,670
animate the torso first throughout the whole animation

48
00:02:13,670 --> 00:02:14,130
and go from there.

49
00:02:14,130 --> 00:02:15,431
I'm way out of my element.

50
00:02:15,431 --> 00:02:16,071
Moving on.

51
00:02:16,071 --> 00:02:17,372
Next tip.

52
00:02:17,372 --> 00:02:21,473
Consider the motion of each element of your character

53
00:02:21,473 --> 00:02:23,994
before animating between the poses.

54
00:02:23,994 --> 00:02:25,534
A good way to avoid problems down the line

55
00:02:25,534 --> 00:02:26,135
in your animation.

56
00:02:26,881 --> 00:02:29,063
is to consider each part of your character in advance,

57
00:02:29,063 --> 00:02:31,445
and not just jump into it and pray that things work out.

58
00:02:31,445 --> 00:02:34,847
For example, with this animation,

59
00:02:34,847 --> 00:02:37,650
I had to really think, how will this snake move?

60
00:02:37,650 --> 00:02:39,051
How will that snake move?

61
00:02:39,051 --> 00:02:40,532
How will that snake move?

62
00:02:40,532 --> 00:02:41,753
How will that snake move?

63
00:02:41,753 --> 00:02:43,594
And oh my God, there's another one too.

64
00:02:43,594 --> 00:02:45,796
Thinking about each part,

65
00:02:45,796 --> 00:02:48,178
I could make sure that everything moves together nicely,

66
00:02:48,178 --> 00:02:50,200
and that there are no problems like

67
00:02:50,200 --> 00:02:52,562
two snakes moving together in the same way at the same time,

68
00:02:52,562 --> 00:02:54,884
the snakes awkwardly overlapping each other,

69
00:02:54,884 --> 00:02:55,384
things like that.

70
00:02:56,210 --> 00:02:57,670
If I didn't think ahead, I could have found

71
00:02:57,670 --> 00:02:58,791
that there were a lot of issues

72
00:02:58,791 --> 00:03:01,452
once I was already knee deep in animating.

73
00:03:01,452 --> 00:03:04,533
The more you figure out before diving into animating,

74
00:03:04,533 --> 00:03:06,474
the better your animation will be

75
00:03:06,474 --> 00:03:07,895
because you're animating thoughtfully.

76
00:03:07,895 --> 00:03:11,036
For 3D folks, I recommend the same thing,

77
00:03:11,036 --> 00:03:12,757
having a plan for each piece of the character

78
00:03:12,757 --> 00:03:14,597
and thoughtfully placing everything

79
00:03:14,597 --> 00:03:17,299
according to that plan as you go along.

80
00:03:17,299 --> 00:03:20,340
If you don't, you may go from stepped to splined

81
00:03:20,340 --> 00:03:23,221
and see that some parts of the character move,

82
00:03:23,221 --> 00:03:25,742
eh, good enough, and just keep it that way.

83
00:03:26,643 --> 00:03:29,745
The more intention you have, the better.

84
00:03:29,745 --> 00:03:33,108
Next tip, rough your poses light and push when tying down.

85
00:03:33,108 --> 00:03:36,851
I think I and many others have a subconscious tendency

86
00:03:36,851 --> 00:03:38,792
to hold things back just a little bit,

87
00:03:38,792 --> 00:03:41,314
even when we think that we're pushing them.

88
00:03:41,314 --> 00:03:43,156
So I often find, even to this day,

89
00:03:43,156 --> 00:03:44,977
my first attempt at a pose or drawing

90
00:03:44,977 --> 00:03:48,040
isn't quite pushed as far as it could be.

91
00:03:48,040 --> 00:03:49,621
Here's an example of a face that I roughed

92
00:03:49,621 --> 00:03:51,122
to show what I mean by this.

93
00:03:52,859 --> 00:03:54,680
After roughing, I went over it clean,

94
00:03:54,680 --> 00:03:56,301
but I pushed things just a little bit.

95
00:03:56,301 --> 00:03:57,521
You can see if you look closely.

96
00:03:57,521 --> 00:04:00,743
The eyebrows go down a tiny bit more in the middle,

97
00:04:00,743 --> 00:04:03,284
the corners of the mouth go just a bit higher,

98
00:04:03,284 --> 00:04:06,145
and the bottom of the mouth goes a little bit lower.

99
00:04:06,145 --> 00:04:08,686
And I find almost always when I do this,

100
00:04:08,686 --> 00:04:10,447
it tends to make things a little bit better

101
00:04:10,447 --> 00:04:12,528
and not a little bit worse.

102
00:04:12,528 --> 00:04:14,369
And for this tip for the 3D folks,

103
00:04:14,369 --> 00:04:16,810
I'd just say, after you pose something out,

104
00:04:16,810 --> 00:04:19,111
just try pushing things a little bit.

105
00:04:19,111 --> 00:04:21,012
You don't know it's too far until you try it.

106
00:04:21,510 --> 00:04:25,271
And unlike on paper, you can just undo.

107
00:04:25,271 --> 00:04:26,912
Sort of.

108
00:04:26,912 --> 00:04:30,393
Next tip, keep your animation sincere.

109
00:04:30,393 --> 00:04:31,334
I think it's much more important

110
00:04:31,334 --> 00:04:33,275
to keep your characters animating sincerely

111
00:04:33,275 --> 00:04:34,955
than it is to try to pack the animation

112
00:04:34,955 --> 00:04:37,536
with as much entertaining motion as possible.

113
00:04:37,536 --> 00:04:39,837
Here's an example from Princess Mononoke.

114
00:04:39,837 --> 00:04:41,058
The motions are pretty simple.

115
00:04:41,058 --> 00:04:42,919
Her head turns just a bit,

116
00:04:42,919 --> 00:04:45,480
her body subtly tenses as she spits the blood,

117
00:04:45,480 --> 00:04:46,720
then she adjusts her posture

118
00:04:46,720 --> 00:04:49,682
and wipes her mouth with a simple motion of her arm.

119
00:04:50,163 --> 00:04:52,744
She doesn't need to ham it up with a lot of extra movement

120
00:04:52,744 --> 00:04:53,965
because that would take you out of the story.

121
00:04:53,965 --> 00:04:57,166
You want people to believe in your characters

122
00:04:57,166 --> 00:04:59,687
as if they were real and see them as alive.

123
00:04:59,687 --> 00:05:02,488
You don't want people to be pulled from that illusion

124
00:05:02,488 --> 00:05:04,429
by too much purposeless movement.

125
00:05:04,429 --> 00:05:06,229
You want every movement to have purpose,

126
00:05:06,229 --> 00:05:08,930
not just to show off that you know how to overshoot things.

127
00:05:08,930 --> 00:05:12,732
In this example, nothing is superfluous.

128
00:05:12,732 --> 00:05:15,393
Simba closes his eyes because the weird monkey man

129
00:05:15,393 --> 00:05:16,833
is dropping some gunk on his head.

130
00:05:17,663 --> 00:05:19,705
He stretches out and wiggles his nose

131
00:05:19,705 --> 00:05:21,126
because he's preparing to sneeze,

132
00:05:21,126 --> 00:05:22,507
and he overshoots with his face

133
00:05:22,507 --> 00:05:25,089
because sneezing is a surprising burst of force

134
00:05:25,089 --> 00:05:26,751
and it causes your face to overshoot.

135
00:05:26,751 --> 00:05:28,892
It's important to make use

136
00:05:28,892 --> 00:05:30,734
of all of the animation principles that you can,

137
00:05:30,734 --> 00:05:33,696
just as long as they actually add to your animation

138
00:05:33,696 --> 00:05:35,377
and don't distract or go against

139
00:05:35,377 --> 00:05:38,260
what the animation needs to accomplish.

140
00:05:38,260 --> 00:05:39,340
Last tip, contrast.

141
00:05:39,340 --> 00:05:42,563
Contrast is one of the most important things,

142
00:05:42,563 --> 00:05:44,765
not only in animation, but in almost everything,

143
00:05:44,765 --> 00:05:46,466
and I think about it a lot when animating.

144
00:05:47,515 --> 00:05:51,017
If you have pose A start out fast and ease into pose B,

145
00:05:51,017 --> 00:05:54,058
and then you have pose B start out fast and ease into pose C,

146
00:05:54,058 --> 00:05:56,919
and C to D, it will be distractingly boring.

147
00:05:56,919 --> 00:05:59,860
It will put the audience into a coma on site.

148
00:05:59,860 --> 00:06:01,400
It would be so boring.

149
00:06:01,400 --> 00:06:03,101
That's why I didn't make an example.

150
00:06:03,101 --> 00:06:04,001
I'm trying to protect you.

151
00:06:04,001 --> 00:06:08,703
In music, you need the contrast of high notes and low notes.

152
00:06:08,703 --> 00:06:12,524
In cooking, you need sweet and you need bitter.

153
00:06:12,524 --> 00:06:16,885
And so in animation, you need fast and slow movement.

154
00:06:17,298 --> 00:06:20,759
steady and erratic movement, big and small movement.

155
00:06:20,759 --> 00:06:24,160
Without any contrast, life would be very boring.

156
00:06:24,160 --> 00:06:26,181
Life needs contrast, and so does animation.

157
00:06:26,181 --> 00:06:26,581
That's it for me.

158
00:06:26,581 --> 00:06:28,561
Thanks, everybody.

159
00:06:28,561 --> 00:06:37,843
Hello, everyone.

160
00:06:37,843 --> 00:06:39,824
