00:06:39,824 --> 00:06:42,064
I'm an animator at the Molasses Flood,

162
00:06:42,064 --> 00:06:44,145
previously at Sony Santa Monica with Melissa.

163
00:06:44,616 --> 00:06:46,718
And today I'm going to be going over my personal animation

164
00:06:46,718 --> 00:06:47,879
philosophies.

165
00:06:47,879 --> 00:06:50,701
I'm going to be quickly going over the importance of workspace,

166
00:06:50,701 --> 00:06:53,043
some camera tips, and some lessons from yoga.

167
00:06:53,043 --> 00:06:56,125
Tip number one, make your workspace work for you.

168
00:06:56,125 --> 00:06:57,466
When I say workspace, I'm talking

169
00:06:57,466 --> 00:07:00,009
about sitting ergonomically, making sure your wrists aren't

170
00:07:00,009 --> 00:07:01,370
straining, using scripts and hotkeys

171
00:07:01,370 --> 00:07:03,812
to automate as much as possible, that sort of thing.

172
00:07:03,812 --> 00:07:06,774
This is what Maya looks like the first time you open it up.

173
00:07:07,374 --> 00:07:09,796
You're presented with 8,000 tools to handle a billion

174
00:07:09,796 --> 00:07:10,417
possible tasks.

175
00:07:10,417 --> 00:07:12,218
So it's your job to curate and make sure

176
00:07:12,218 --> 00:07:15,161
you're being as efficient as possible with which tools

177
00:07:15,161 --> 00:07:17,443
you're using and how your tools are arranged.

178
00:07:17,443 --> 00:07:18,964
Seems pretty obvious, but you want

179
00:07:18,964 --> 00:07:20,325
to make sure you're set up for success

180
00:07:20,325 --> 00:07:22,627
before you even start animating.

181
00:07:22,627 --> 00:07:24,729
An efficient workspace is going to make you faster,

182
00:07:24,729 --> 00:07:27,231
which is going to make you a more valuable animator.

183
00:07:27,231 --> 00:07:29,213
As animators, we do a lot of repetitive operations

184
00:07:29,213 --> 00:07:30,274
throughout the day.

185
00:07:30,274 --> 00:07:32,375
So if you can cut a few seconds each time,

186
00:07:32,375 --> 00:07:35,138
that's going to save you a lot of time in the long term.

187
00:07:35,572 --> 00:07:37,073
We want to keep thinking about the long term

188
00:07:37,073 --> 00:07:38,294
and work smart more than hard.

189
00:07:38,294 --> 00:07:42,276
Our risks are essential to our livelihoods

190
00:07:42,276 --> 00:07:44,837
and RSI, carpal tunnel, these are real threats

191
00:07:44,837 --> 00:07:46,318
we need to be diligent about preventing

192
00:07:46,318 --> 00:07:47,879
and we can do that with a proper workspace.

193
00:07:47,879 --> 00:07:50,940
And to that I say consider switching to a tablet

194
00:07:50,940 --> 00:07:53,521
or a vertical mouse at least.

195
00:07:53,521 --> 00:07:55,362
Might feel weird or slow you down temporarily

196
00:07:55,362 --> 00:07:57,243
but for me it has sped up my workflow

197
00:07:57,243 --> 00:07:59,685
probably more than anything else.

198
00:07:59,685 --> 00:08:01,926
So if you can, give it a shot, I highly recommend it.

199
00:08:01,926 --> 00:08:03,367
As far as animation tools go.

200
00:08:03,888 --> 00:08:05,109
There's tons of great stuff out there,

201
00:08:05,109 --> 00:08:06,409
so I just wanted to highlight some scripts

202
00:08:06,409 --> 00:08:06,749
that I use a lot.

203
00:08:06,749 --> 00:08:09,530
I use a lot of stuff from Aaron Carusel,

204
00:08:09,530 --> 00:08:11,991
who's an Animation Tools Lead at Pixar.

205
00:08:11,991 --> 00:08:13,632
On his site, he's got a bunch of stuff.

206
00:08:13,632 --> 00:08:15,072
If you work heavy in the graph editor,

207
00:08:15,072 --> 00:08:17,013
there's lots of scripts for flipping curves,

208
00:08:17,013 --> 00:08:19,033
pushing, pulling curves, making loops

209
00:08:19,033 --> 00:08:21,054
based on nearby keys.

210
00:08:21,054 --> 00:08:23,635
Really great stuff if you work heavy in the graph editor.

211
00:08:23,635 --> 00:08:24,655
Go to his site, check that out.

212
00:08:24,655 --> 00:08:26,916
There might be something there to speed up your workflow.

213
00:08:26,916 --> 00:08:30,437
Tip number two, let's talk about cameras.

214
00:08:31,043 --> 00:08:32,364
I know we don't all have the ability

215
00:08:32,364 --> 00:08:35,065
to have animatable cameras in our games,

216
00:08:35,065 --> 00:08:37,426
but if you do, learning more about the features of a camera

217
00:08:37,426 --> 00:08:40,007
can help bring your animation to the next level.

218
00:08:40,007 --> 00:08:42,147
We all understand how important composition is,

219
00:08:42,147 --> 00:08:44,588
but do we understand focal length or depth of field?

220
00:08:44,588 --> 00:08:46,129
Learn these things.

221
00:08:46,129 --> 00:08:48,370
Just like composition, a focal length

222
00:08:48,370 --> 00:08:51,851
is gonna evoke a certain feeling or mood.

223
00:08:51,851 --> 00:08:53,772
You wanna make sure you're using the correct one

224
00:08:53,772 --> 00:08:55,632
that's gonna emphasize what you're already

225
00:08:55,632 --> 00:08:57,093
trying to say in your shots.

226
00:08:57,093 --> 00:08:59,074
A shot's gonna feel more dramatic or more intimate

227
00:08:59,074 --> 00:09:00,114
depending on a focal length.

228
00:09:01,101 --> 00:09:03,782
Every piece of the camera is a decision that we make.

229
00:09:03,782 --> 00:09:05,903
And by leaving the camera at default settings,

230
00:09:05,903 --> 00:09:06,903
that's a decision too.

231
00:09:06,903 --> 00:09:08,904
But somebody else has made it for you.

232
00:09:08,904 --> 00:09:10,824
So learn these pieces so that you can better make

233
00:09:10,824 --> 00:09:13,045
the decisions for yourself.

234
00:09:13,045 --> 00:09:15,646
And again, if you have the ability to have a camera,

235
00:09:15,646 --> 00:09:17,207
really take advantage of that and emphasize

236
00:09:17,207 --> 00:09:18,367
action with camera movement.

237
00:09:18,367 --> 00:09:21,208
This is a really early rough blocking of a camera sync

238
00:09:21,208 --> 00:09:23,149
move from God of War.

239
00:09:23,149 --> 00:09:26,350
You can see, especially when we remove the background elements,

240
00:09:26,350 --> 00:09:28,971
that Kratos doesn't actually move within the frame very much.

241
00:09:28,971 --> 00:09:30,752
So on a later pass, what we did was.

242
00:09:31,166 --> 00:09:33,087
basically swung the camera left and right

243
00:09:33,087 --> 00:09:35,988
during the high action moments to put Kratos closer

244
00:09:35,988 --> 00:09:38,829
to the edges of the frame so that he takes up more space

245
00:09:38,829 --> 00:09:40,749
on the big movements.

246
00:09:40,749 --> 00:09:44,611
And you can see how that compares with the before

247
00:09:44,611 --> 00:09:48,092
and after.

248
00:09:48,092 --> 00:09:50,713
So really take advantage if you have the ability

249
00:09:50,713 --> 00:09:53,173
to have an animatable camera.

250
00:09:53,173 --> 00:09:53,974
