they didn't have to open any software that they weren't familiar with.

514
00:22:42,448 --> 00:22:50,471
Another example can be found in how animation can be informed by the mechanics of the game.

515
00:22:50,471 --> 00:22:55,073
This is especially easy to do in character cinematics or things like highlight intros,

516
00:22:55,073 --> 00:23:00,135
but collaborating with a designer will make your animations so much more effective in the game.

517
00:23:00,135 --> 00:23:02,796
This will also help give context to the game mechanics,

518
00:23:02,796 --> 00:23:05,477
and it's always better to show rather than to tell.

519
00:23:06,724 --> 00:23:10,005
Last year, Aubert was working on a game called Super Random Heroes,

520
00:23:10,005 --> 00:23:12,526
and I created this intro cinematic for a mini-boss.

521
00:23:12,526 --> 00:23:16,167
The enemy does a jumping attack where he tries to land on the player,

522
00:23:16,167 --> 00:23:17,447
so I put that right in the cinematic.

523
00:23:17,447 --> 00:23:20,488
This gave a lot of context to the mini-boss

524
00:23:20,488 --> 00:23:26,130
and created an opportunity for players to feel smart for picking up on it.

525
00:23:26,130 --> 00:23:27,951
Now let's flip it.

526
00:23:27,951 --> 00:23:30,151
How can animation help my design skills?

527
00:23:30,151 --> 00:23:34,293
I want to use the principles of animation as an example.

528
00:23:35,138 --> 00:23:38,579
What perspective can they give to a design?

529
00:23:38,579 --> 00:23:41,820
Well, I consider things like, how much time

530
00:23:41,820 --> 00:23:44,641
am I giving the players to learn something?

531
00:23:44,641 --> 00:23:48,002
How do I anticipate a design beat in the game?

532
00:23:48,002 --> 00:23:49,562
Can I anticipate player progression?

533
00:23:49,562 --> 00:23:53,983
How can you use staging to draw attention throughout a level?

534
00:23:53,983 --> 00:23:57,324
Or what order am I presenting things?

535
00:23:57,324 --> 00:24:00,184
How many things am I requiring the player to mentally keep

536
00:24:00,184 --> 00:24:00,925
track of at once?

537
00:24:02,045 --> 00:24:07,208
This kind of thing is really useful to me, since using it as a lens to see my own work differently

538
00:24:07,208 --> 00:24:10,530
allows me to ask myself questions that I wouldn't have otherwise thought of.

539
00:24:10,530 --> 00:24:17,754
Another interesting perspective that animation can give design is visual language. Games are

540
00:24:17,754 --> 00:24:21,617
interacting with a system that's behaving in a specific way. At the end of the day,

541
00:24:21,617 --> 00:24:26,139
you're communicating an emotion or some kind of information without words.

542
00:24:26,139 --> 00:24:30,962
Designs can use words, but generally I think it's more engaging to not.

543
00:24:32,446 --> 00:24:35,468
I worked on both the level design and animation

544
00:24:35,468 --> 00:24:38,410
for Vertex Pop's new game, Super Crush KO,

545
00:24:38,410 --> 00:24:42,333
and I needed to use my skills through both disciplines

546
00:24:42,333 --> 00:24:45,495
to communicate with the team to communicate

547
00:24:45,495 --> 00:24:46,896
the visual language of the game.

548
00:24:46,896 --> 00:24:50,038
I hope this gives you an idea of how you can learn

549
00:24:50,038 --> 00:24:52,319
from other perspectives or workflows

550
00:24:52,319 --> 00:24:54,141
to improve your own work.

551
00:24:54,141 --> 00:24:56,222
It can be a lens to critique,

552
00:24:56,222 --> 00:24:58,604
or a basis for your approach for something entirely new.

553
00:24:58,604 --> 00:25:00,345
And the best part is,

554
00:25:00,905 --> 00:25:04,005
You can learn this from the people already around you.

555
00:25:04,005 --> 00:25:06,286
This can be coworkers, dev friends,

556
00:25:06,286 --> 00:25:08,826
or people that you just met on the street.

557
00:25:08,826 --> 00:25:14,268
So, the problem is, seeing something

558
00:25:14,268 --> 00:25:16,228
from another perspective can be unsettling at first.

559
00:25:16,228 --> 00:25:17,668
So I want to try and leave you with a couple tips

560
00:25:17,668 --> 00:25:19,729
on how you can do this on your own.

561
00:25:19,729 --> 00:25:21,789
Try asking someone, what do they consider

562
00:25:21,789 --> 00:25:22,649
before they start work?

563
00:25:22,649 --> 00:25:25,910
What principles do they follow as they work?

564
00:25:25,910 --> 00:25:27,510
And my personal favorite.

565
00:25:28,204 --> 00:25:31,265
What criteria do they use to measure the quality of their own work?

566
00:25:31,265 --> 00:25:38,228
And as a bonus, you might find a more creative solution to a problem you're having.

567
00:25:38,228 --> 00:25:38,488
Thank you.

568
00:25:38,488 --> 00:25:38,688
APPLAUSE

569
00:25:38,688 --> 00:25:49,272
Oh, okay. Hi, I'm Melissa Shim,

570
00:25:49,272 --> 00:25:53,013
and I'm currently a senior animator at Sony Santa Monica.

571
00:25:53,013 --> 00:25:55,814
I most recently worked on God of War.

572
00:25:56,318 --> 00:25:57,978
and a lot of other things before that.

573
00:25:57,978 --> 00:26:01,920
So I'll be covering some tips and tricks about networking

574
00:26:01,920 --> 00:26:03,841
and job hunting.

575
00:26:03,841 --> 00:26:05,941
And I think they're applicable whether you're

576
00:26:05,941 --> 00:26:08,642
new to the industry or you've been doing this for a while.

577
00:26:08,642 --> 00:26:12,564
First off, I'd like to say that networking can be super awkward.

578
00:26:12,564 --> 00:26:17,305
However, if you're just starting out, over time,

579
00:26:17,305 --> 00:26:19,686
it'll get easier.

580
00:26:19,686 --> 00:26:22,567
While networking can also seem self-serving,

581
00:26:22,567 --> 00:26:23,968
I don't think it really has to be.

582
00:26:23,968 --> 00:26:25,668
We're all here to help each other out.

583
00:26:25,668 --> 00:26:25,748
So.

584
00:26:26,807 --> 00:26:29,750
Just be yourself and be genuine with your interactions.

585
00:26:29,750 --> 00:26:31,831
My first topic is etiquette.

586
00:26:31,831 --> 00:26:33,152
Provide a reason to connect.

587
00:26:33,152 --> 00:26:39,577
Part of networking is to reach out to as many people as possible.

588
00:26:39,577 --> 00:26:45,222
However, I don't necessarily think that quantity is better over quality.

589
00:26:45,222 --> 00:26:50,466
When I started networking online specifically, I would usually contact an animator at a studio

590
00:26:50,466 --> 00:26:54,889
I was interested in and see if they had some time to answer some questions.

591
00:26:55,445 --> 00:26:59,648
I believe that striking up a conversation with the other person actually provides a

592
00:26:59,648 --> 00:27:01,689
more authentic and therefore useful connection.

593
00:27:01,689 --> 00:27:05,792
Keep in mind that not everyone will respond to you, nor are they obligated to.

594
00:27:05,792 --> 00:27:09,615
This is totally normal and nothing to take personally.

595
00:27:09,615 --> 00:27:12,517
Be professional.

596
00:27:12,517 --> 00:27:14,539
This is a pretty obvious one.

597
00:27:14,539 --> 00:27:19,322
If you're looking for information or for mentorship, showing gratitude with a please and thank

598
00:27:19,322 --> 00:27:22,024
you and respecting their time and space will go a long way.

599
00:27:22,627 --> 00:27:25,869
especially if that person has taken time out of their day to help you out.

600
00:27:25,869 --> 00:27:32,414
I also would love to advise against using Facebook as a way to connect with someone

601
00:27:32,414 --> 00:27:35,516
you've never spoken to or you've never met in person before.

602
00:27:35,516 --> 00:27:41,239
Honestly, you don't want someone like me to post a picture of you from 10 years ago doing

603
00:27:41,239 --> 00:27:43,061
drunk limbo, right Simon?

604
00:27:43,061 --> 00:27:51,927
So if you're looking for a professional connection, please use these platforms instead.

605
00:27:53,964 --> 00:27:58,908
My second main topic is to know yourself and your audience.

606
00:27:58,908 --> 00:28:00,790
Have clear goals of what you want to accomplish,

607
00:28:00,790 --> 00:28:02,671
and ask yourself if the move you're making

608
00:28:02,671 --> 00:28:05,053
is in the right direction or not.

609
00:28:05,053 --> 00:28:07,155
When deciding on a piece of work you want to do,

610
00:28:07,155 --> 00:28:08,596
choose something that really excites you.

611
00:28:08,596 --> 00:28:10,818
Your love for an idea will actually

612
00:28:10,818 --> 00:28:13,220
show more than you realize in your final product,

613
00:28:13,220 --> 00:28:15,542
and therefore make it stand out.

614
00:28:15,542 --> 00:28:21,087
Here's an example of a piece I did back in 2014.

615
00:28:21,636 --> 00:28:23,677
I didn't really create this to get a job

616
00:28:23,677 --> 00:28:25,017
at any specific studio.

617
00:28:25,017 --> 00:28:29,779
I had a great admiration for work for games like this,

618
00:28:29,779 --> 00:28:33,881
and lo and behold, a year a bit later, I ended up at Sony.

619
00:28:33,881 --> 00:28:39,123
Be self-aware of your work.

620
00:28:39,123 --> 00:28:42,364
And what I mean by this is to be honest and realistic

621
00:28:42,364 --> 00:28:45,085
about where the quality of your work stands.

622
00:28:45,085 --> 00:28:47,907
Compare your work to the goal studios you have in mind,

623
00:28:47,907 --> 00:28:50,908
as well as to other animators at your experience level.

624
00:28:51,571 --> 00:28:53,392
Find areas where you can improve,

625
00:28:53,392 --> 00:28:55,293
and if asking for feedback, point these out.

626
00:28:55,293 --> 00:28:58,956
Also remember to be kind to yourself during this process.

627
00:28:58,956 --> 00:29:01,357
You can always aim for the stars,

628
00:29:01,357 --> 00:29:05,180
but be aware of what it will take to get there.

629
00:29:05,180 --> 00:29:06,781
Do your research.

630
00:29:06,781 --> 00:29:07,721
Be familiar with the studio

631
00:29:07,721 --> 00:29:09,262
and the position you're interested in,

632
00:29:09,262 --> 00:29:11,164
the history of their games,

633
00:29:11,164 --> 00:29:12,985
their work culture, management style,

634
00:29:12,985 --> 00:29:15,106
and get as much detail as you can

635
00:29:15,106 --> 00:29:17,368
on the position you're applying for.

636
00:29:17,368 --> 00:29:18,588
As much as they're looking to see

637
00:29:18,588 --> 00:29:19,609
if you're a right fit for them,

638
00:29:20,229 --> 00:29:23,791
you want to ensure that they're a right fit for you.

639
00:29:23,791 --> 00:29:26,433
My final main topic is to always be learning.

640
00:29:26,433 --> 00:29:29,074
I learned how to do that in one night.

641
00:29:29,074 --> 00:29:33,016
Don't be afraid to ask for feedback,

642
00:29:33,016 --> 00:29:37,759
whether it's regarding personal animation, how you interviewed,

643
00:29:37,759 --> 00:29:39,800
or how you're performing at work.

644
00:29:39,800 --> 00:29:42,102
Constructive criticism is crucial for growth.

645
00:29:42,102 --> 00:29:45,083
For example, some years ago, I had done an animation test

646
00:29:45,083 --> 00:29:46,204
which I had not passed.

647
00:29:46,683 --> 00:29:49,144
the team was actually more than happy to provide me

648
00:29:49,144 --> 00:29:52,207
with some great feedback I could use going forward.

649
00:29:52,207 --> 00:29:55,148
Not all studios will be able to do this for you,

650
00:29:55,148 --> 00:29:58,971
but it's never, you know, don't be afraid to ask, basically.

651
00:29:58,971 --> 00:30:01,193
Finally, don't let failure get you down.

652
00:30:01,193 --> 00:30:03,954
It's often looked at as a negative thing,

653
00:30:03,954 --> 00:30:06,216
but there's so much that we can learn from it,

654
00:30:06,216 --> 00:30:09,258
and you really never know where it'll bring you.

655
00:30:09,258 --> 00:30:11,179
In 2013, my goal was to break into

656
00:30:11,179 --> 00:30:12,960
the visual effects industry by the end of the year,

657
00:30:12,960 --> 00:30:14,622
and that never actually happened.

658
00:30:15,278 --> 00:30:17,659
But with each job I took subsequently,

659
00:30:17,659 --> 00:30:19,420
it ended up bringing me to Sony Santa Monica,

660
00:30:19,420 --> 00:30:22,722
where I've worked on some of the most exciting and challenging

661
00:30:22,722 --> 00:30:24,222
animations of my career.

662
00:30:24,222 --> 00:30:29,245
So in conclusion, being respectful and polite,

663
00:30:29,245 --> 00:30:32,906
practicing self-awareness, and remaining open to growth

664
00:30:32,906 --> 00:30:35,687
will go a long way in maintaining a strong career.

665
00:30:35,687 --> 00:30:36,768
Thank you for your time.

